###### Theorem 5.

Let X be a quasiaffine spherical G-variety and let R be a B-root subgroup on X. Let Y\subset X^{\operatorname{reg}} be a G-orbit such that all B-stable prime divisors in X not containing Y are R-stable. Suppose that R connects Y with a G-orbit Y^{\prime} such that Y\subset\overline{Y^{\prime}}. Then Y^{\prime} is minimal with the property Y\subset\overline{Y^{\prime}} and RY=Y\cup Y^{\prime}.

###### Proof.

It follows from the hypothesis that the vanishing set of the function f from Theorem 3 is R-stable, so the action of R can be restricted to X\_{f}. Since R commutes with U, it permutes P\_{u}-orbits, so there exists an R-equivariant quotient map \pi\_{Z}\colon X\_{f}\rightarrow Z as well as the restriction of the action of R to \mathbb{K}[X\_{f}]^{P\_{u}}=\mathbb{K}[Z]. In particular, a G-orbit Y^{\prime}\supset Y can be connected with Y via R if and only if Y^{\prime}\cap Z can be connected with Z\_{Y} via the action of R on Z.
The action of R on Z still commutes with U\_{L}. This implies that R preserves the U\_{L}-fixed point set Z^{U\_{L}}\simeq L\*\_{L\_{0}}N\_{z}^{U\_{L}}\simeq T\*\_{T\_{0}}N\_{z}^{U\_{L}}.
Since Z\_{Y}\subset Z^{U\_{L}}, the set Y^{\prime}\cap Z can be connected with Z\_{Y} by R only if Y^{\prime}\cap Z\subset Z^{U\_{L}}.
Observe that Z^{U\_{L}} is a toric T-variety and the restriction of R to Z^{U\_{L}} is a T-root subgroup. It is well known that in this case any pair of T-orbits O\_{1},O\_{2}\subset Z^{U\_{L}} connected by R satisfy \dim O\_{1}-\dim O\_{2}=\pm 1.
Then every G-orbit Y^{\prime} satisfying Y\subset\overline{Y^{\prime}} and connected with Y via R satisfies \dim(Y^{\prime}\cap Z)=\dim Z\_{Y}+1, hence Y^{\prime} is minimal among all G-orbits properly containing Y in their closure.
